## 🧩 Why Network Models Exist

Without a shared standard, two devices communicating would need to agree on everything from scratch — addressing, language, packaging, transport, interpretation. Network models solve this by **breaking communication into layers**, where each layer:

- Has one specific job
- Doesn't need to know how other layers work
- Passes data to the layer above/below through a defined interface

---

## 🧱 The OSI Model (7 Layers) — Theoretical Blueprint

Developed by ISO. Not directly implemented as-is in modern networks, but essential for **conceptual understanding** and dissecting traffic for security work.

| Layer | Name | Responsibility | Examples/Protocols | Analogy |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 7 | **Application** | Services directly for user apps | HTTP/HTTPS, SMTP, POP3, IMAP, FTP, Telnet, SSH | The message content/language |
| 6 | **Presentation** | Data formatting, encryption, compression | SSL/TLS, JPEG, MPEG | Translating/encrypting the message |
| 5 | **Session** | Establish, manage, terminate sessions | NetBIOS, RPC | Managing a phone call |
| 4 | **Transport** | Host-to-host delivery, segmentation, flow/error control | **TCP** (reliable), **UDP** (best-effort) | Registered mail (TCP) vs postcard (UDP) |
| 3 | **Network** | Logical addressing & routing | IP, ICMP, ARP | Road network + traffic police |
| 2 | **Data Link** | Physical (MAC) addressing, framing, error detection | Ethernet, Wi-Fi (802.11), PPP | Specific road + license plates |
| 1 | **Physical** | Raw bit transmission over medium | Cat5e/6 cables, fiber, radio, RJ45 | The physical road/tires |

**Mnemonic (top→bottom):** *All People Seem To Need Data Processing*

